howToBreak.description:
### How to Break It

The most fragile parts of this code are the concurrency logic in the goroutine loop and the handling of the `workerCount` variable. Incorrect changes to how goroutines are launched or how results are collected from the channel can easily introduce deadlocks, race conditions, or missed results.

A common beginner mistake is to accidentally capture the loop variable `i` incorrectly inside the goroutine closure. In Go, the loop variable is shared across all goroutines, so if you change the goroutine definition on line 28 from:

```go
go func() {
    if i != 0 {
        task.Definition().Seed = infrastructure.GenerateSeed()
    }
    // ...
}()
```

to:

```go
go func() {
    // use i here
}()
```

without passing `i` as an argument to the closure, all goroutines may see the final value of `i` instead of their intended index. This can cause all goroutines to behave identically, potentially skipping seed generation or corrupting task processing. To fix this, always pass `i` as a parameter:

```go
go func(i int) {
    if i != 0 {
        task.Definition().Seed = infrastructure.GenerateSeed()
    }
    // ...
}(i)
```

This ensures each goroutine gets its own copy of `i`, preventing subtle concurrency bugs.

