### How to Break It

The most fragile parts of this code are the interface definitions and the struct field types. Changing method signatures in interfaces like `LLMProvider`, `TokenStreamingProvider`, or `ByteOperationProvider` can easily break implementations or consumers. Similarly, altering the types or names of fields in request or config structs (e.g., `AudioGenerationRequest`, `GenerationConfig`) can cause runtime errors or compilation failures if dependent code expects the original structure.

A common beginner mistake is to accidentally change the type of a struct field. For example, in the `GenerationConfig` struct, if you change the `Temperature` field from `float64` to `int`:

```go
type GenerationConfig struct {
    Model         string
    Temperature   int // <-- Mistake: should be float64
    MaxTokens     int
    // ...
}
```

This will break any code that assigns a floating-point value to `Temperature`, such as in the `DefaultGenerationConfig()` function:

```go
return &GenerationConfig{
    Temperature:   0.7, // Error: cannot use 0.7 (type float64) as type int
    // ...
}
```

This type mismatch will cause a compilation error, preventing the code from building. Always ensure field types match their intended usage, especially when default values or calculations rely on specific types.

